      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ [He is extremely busy with his garden. Prince Paul Wilhelm was there for a long time and had many conversations with Dr. Mueller. ¶ Prince Paul Wilhelm of Württemberg; see M to E. Fenzl, 14 Septemb...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="de">58.11.16</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="de">To Wilhelm Sonder</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Letter not<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>seen. The text given here is extracted from Tkach, Neubauer &amp; Roser (2022), Brief<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>33,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>W. Sonder to D.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>von Schlechtendal,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>10 January 1859.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The extract is introduced by 'Von Dr. F. Müller hatte ich gestern einen vom 16 Nov. datirten Brief' [Yesterday I received a letter from Dr. F. Mueller, dated 16 November].</p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[Er ist überaus beschäftigt mit seinem Garten. Der Prinz Paul Wilhelm war längere Zeit dort u verkehrte viel mit Dr. Müller. Die östreichische Fregatte war in Sidney angekommen. Dr. Müller erwartete sie in Melbourne. Es sollte gerade eine Kiste mit Drucksachen u Pflanzen für mich abgehen.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>—<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Ich sende Ihnen hierbei eine Doublette vom 2 Heft der Transact. der pharmac. Society; es ist darin ein Rhus beschrieben u wird es Sie vielleicht interessieren zu lesen, wie wenig die englischen Apotheken<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Apotheker?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>geneigt sind Reformen in der Pharmacie anzunehmen.....</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="de">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dr. Müller schreibt, dass die Abdrucke der Rhamneen von Reisseck lange auf sich warten lassen.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This text is from the penultimate paragraph of the letter, following a discussion of the contents of some of M's papers, see n. 7 below.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>]</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="line-height: 0.1944in; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>[He is extremely busy with his garden. Prince Paul Wilhelm was there for a long time and had many conversations with Dr. Mueller.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>Prince Paul Wilhelm of Württemberg; see M to E. Fenzl, 14 September 1858.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The Austrian frigate had arrived in Sidney.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">i.e. Sydney.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>An Austrian scientific expedition visited Australia and New Zealand in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="tei-seg" style="font-style: italic; ">Novara</seg>;<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>see Scherzer (1861-2).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Dr Mueller was expecting her in Melbourne. A crate with printed matter and plants was about to leave for me.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>—<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I am sending you herewith a duplicate of the second part of the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Transactions of the Pharmaceutical Society</seg>; a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
               <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Rhus</seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>is described in it<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn5" n="6">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Rhus rhodanthema</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(B58.04.01, p. 43).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and it may interest you to read how little the English pharmacies<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn6" n="7">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>pharmacists?</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>are inclined to accept reforms in pharmacy.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn7" n="8">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; margin-left: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont"
                             style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; font-size: 10pt; ">This is not available on line, so I can't gloss the comment "…<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">how little the English pharmaci</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">ists</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>are inclined to accept reforms in pharmacy." It really should have a gloss. I assume it is in another part of the issue where M described the Rhus</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">. Said to be at Monash University</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">.</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">seem to remember that you checked some entries in Ms pubs list at<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-weight: bold; color: #C00000; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>School of Pharmacy site.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>]<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn8" n="9">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Sonder then answers questions<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>Schlechtendal<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>had<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>evidently<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>asked<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">about M publications</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>previously received<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(German text at<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Tkach, Neubauer &amp; Roser (2022),<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>p. 152):</p>
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; margin-left: 0.6298in; text-indent: 0in; "
                        xml:lang="en">The Fragmenta phytographiae. Australasiae is a small independent work, I received the end of the first part via London a few days ago. Our copies of it will probably arrive with the next consignment of plants<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>[<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">B57.07.01</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">:</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">f</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">ascicle 3 of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Fragmenta</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>was accompanied by a title page indicating that it completed vol</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">.</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>1, but when issued as a bound volume (B60.02.04)</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">,</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>vol</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">.</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>1 comprised the first 10 fascicles</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">;</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>see Darragh &amp; Lucas (2015), pp. 303-4]</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">.</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>The Introduction of useful Plants into Victoria,<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 9pt; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>[<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">B58.05.02]<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>as well as An historical Review of the Explorations of Australia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>[<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">B58.05.03]<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>are from the Transactions of the Philosophical Institute. Victoria Vol. II. Part II. I also received: Papers of the Royal Society of Tasmania 1857 p. 227. On Two alpine Eurybiae of the Australian Continent by Dr Ferd. Mueller.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>[<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">B60.13.03</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">:</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the paper is dated 'Botanic Gardens, Melbourne, January 1857' and was probably read at a meeting of the Society in February 1857</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">;</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>M evidently received page proofs before the volume was issued, and<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Sonder then lists the species described]<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>On Australian &amp; Tasmanian Umbelliferous Plants by Dr. F. Müller<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>[B<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">60.13.02</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">; Sonder summari</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">z</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">es the content</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">and lists species discussed</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">, and</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Schlechtendal<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>published a lightly edited version of Sonder's summary in<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'Literatur. Papers of the Royal Society of Tasmania. 1857',<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Botanische Zeitung,</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>11 February 1859, p.<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>56, which also<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>mentioned the<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Eurybia</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>paper and listed the new species<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>'nach gütiger Mittheilung des Hrn. Dr. Sonder'<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>[according to the friendly notification of Dr Sonder].</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>...</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="line-height: 0.1944in; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dr Mueller writes that the reprints of Reisseck's Rhamneae are a long time coming.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="font-size: 8pt; ">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn9" n="10">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3347in; text-indent: -0.3347in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>This text is from the penultimate paragraph of the letter, and follows the discussion described in n. 7 above.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>]</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
         </div>
      </body>
